- **Material Type**: Plastic injection bottles dominate the market due to their lightweight nature, durability, and cost-effectiveness. Glass injection bottles are favored for their premium look and recyclability. Other materials used include Polyethylene Terephthalate (PET), Polypropylene (PP), Polyvinyl Chloride (PVC), High Density Polyethylene, Low Density Polyethylene, Linear Low Density Polyethylene, and others.
- **Application**: Injection bottles are widely used in various applications such as Chinese medicine, chemical injection, and others, catering to different industry requirements.
- **Capacity**: Injection bottles come in different capacities ranging from 11-20 ml, 21-30 ml, and more than 30 ml to meet the diverse packaging needs of different industries.
- **Type**: Different types of injection bottles include Type I, Type II, Type III, each designed for specific applications and industry requirements.
- **Shape**: Injection bottles are available in various shapes such as round, hexagon, and others, adding versatility and visual appeal to the packaging.
- **End Users**: Industries utilizing injection bottles include automotive, packaging, building and construction, electrical and electronics, medical, and others, each with unique demands for packaging materials and design.

